"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-medal-picks-predictions-paris-2024-olympics\", \"text\": \"Check out Sports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daily Rings, our daily Olympics podcast from Mitch Goldich and Dan Gartland. Subscribe wherever you get your podcasts (Apple,Spotify) and find clips onSI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s YouTube page.  After an Olympic cycle that saw a delayed Summer Games in Tokyo without any fans and a stripped-down atmosphere at the Winter Games in Beijing, Paris 2024 has finally arrived to bring the world-class competition back to its intended glory. Athletes (and their fans) from more than 200 nations will gather in the City of Light, where some of Paris\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s most iconic spots will be used as venues\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094beach volleyball at the Eiffel Tower, equestrian at the Palace of Versailles and, of course, tennis at Roland-Garros. Below,Sports Illustratedcontributor Brian Cazeneuve predicts the winner for each gold, silver and bronze medal that will be awarded in 329 events from July 26 through Aug. 11.  Gold:Mete Gazoz (Turkiye)Silver:Marcus D\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Almeida (Brazil)Bronze:Kim Woojin (South Korea)  Gazoz would be the first archer to win individual golds at consecutive Olympics.  Gold:South KoreaSilver:JapanBronze:Netherlands  This event has been held at nine Olympics. South Korea has won eight medals, including six golds.  Gold:Alejandra Valencia (Mexico)Silver:Marie Hora\\u00cc\\u0081c\\u00cc\\u008ckova\\u00cc\\u0081 (Czechia)Bronze:Casey Kaufhold (U.S.)  Kaufhold shot her first bow at 3 years old.  Gold:South KoreaSilver:GermanyBronze:France  This event has been held at nine Olympics. South Korea has won gold every time.  Gold:South KoreaSilver:GermanyBronze:Taiwan  Victorious Koreans shot a rare Robin Hood arrow in Tokyo when An San\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s shot went directly through Kim Je Deok\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s arrow.  Gold:Kunlavut Vitidsarn (Thailand)Silver:Viktor Axelsen (Denmark)Bronze:Kodai Naraoka (Japan)  Axelsen lives in dry Dubai because he suffers from asthma and rhinitis.  Gold:Seo Seung-jae and Kang Min-hyuk (South Korea)Silver:Aaron Chia and Soh Wooi Yik (Malaysia)Bronze:Kim Astrup and Anders Skaarup Rasmussen (Denmark)  In 2023, Seo won both men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s doubles and mixed doubles at worlds.  Gold:Akane Yamaguchi (Japan)Silver:An Se-young (South Korea)Bronze:Chen Yufei (China)  At 15, Yamaguchi became the youngest player to join the Japanese national team.  Gold:Chen Qingchen and Jia Yifan (China)Silver:Baek Ha-na and Lee So-hee (South Korea)Bronze:Apriyani Rahayu and Siti Ramadhanti (Indonesia)  Indonesia has won eight Olympic golds, all in badminton.\\u00c2  Gold:Zheng Siwei and Huang Yaqiong (China)Silver:Seo Seung-jae and Chae Yu Jung (South Korea)Bronze:Yuta Watanabe and Arisa Higashino (Japan)  China won a medal in each badminton discipline at the Tokyo Games.  Gold:U.S.Silver:SerbiaBronze:Germany  Germany topped the U.S., 113\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093111, in the 2023 World Cup semifinals.  Gold:U.S.Silver:AustraliaBronze:China  The U.S. outscored foes by 96 points over six games to win gold in Tokyo.\\u00c2  Gold:SerbiaSilver:LatviaBronze:U.S.  The U.S. roster features NBA journeyman Jimmer Fredette and Canyon Barry, son of Hall of Famer Rick.  Gold:U.S.Silver:FranceBronze:China  Dearica Hamby replaces injured Cameron Brink on the U.S. squad.  Gold:Hasanboy Dusmatov (Uzbekistan)Silver:Billal Bennama (France)Bronze:Patrick Chinyemba (Zambia)Bronze:Junior Alcantara (Dominican Republic)  At the 2023 World Boxing Championships in Tashkent, hometown favorite Dusmatov knocked out Bennama.  Gold:Abdumalik Khalokov (Uzbekistan)Silver:Saidel Horta (Cuba)Bronze:Munarek Seitbek Uulu (Kyrgyzstan)Bronze:Jahmal Harvey (U.S.)  Harvey\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s gold at Worlds at age 18 in 2021 made him the first U.S. male boxer to win an amateur title since 2007.  Gold:Sofiane Oumiha (France)Silver:Erislandy \\u00c3\\u0081lvarez (Cuba)Bronze:Radoslav Rosenov (Bulgaria)Bronze:Wyatt Sanford (Canada)  Sanford\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s wife is Canadian Olympic diver Pamela Ware.  Gold:Sewon Okazawa (Japan)Silver:Asadkhuja Muydinkhujaev (Uzbekistan)Bronze:Aslanbek Shymbergenov (Kazakhstan)Bronze:Marco Verde (Mexico)  Okazawa\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s full name is Sewonrets Quincy Mensah Okazawa. His father hails from Ghana.  Gold:Arlen Lopez (Cuba)Silver:Wanderley Pereira (Brazil)Bronze:Tuohetaerbieke Tanglatihan (China)Bronze:Moreno Fendero (France)  From Xinjiang, an autonomous region in northwestern China, Tanatqan was born to Kazhak parents.\\u00c2  Gold:Julio C\\u00c3\\u00a9sar La Cruz (Cuba)Silver:Aziz Abbes Mouhiidine (Italy)Bronze:Lazizbek Mullojonov (Uzbekistan)Bronze:Keno Machado (Brazil)  Cuba has won 41 Olympic golds in boxing; no more than 11 in any other sport.\\u00c2  Gold:Bakhodir Jalolov (Uzbekistan)Silver:Ayoub Ghadfa (Spain)Bronze:Mahammad Abdullayev (Azerbaijan)Bronze:Davit Chaloyan (Armenia)  This class features a British boxer named Delicious Orie.  Gold:Buse Naz C\\u00cc\\u00a7ak\\u00c4\\u00b1rogelu (Turkiye)Silver:Wu Yu (China)Bronze:Nikhat Zareen (India)Bronze:Giordana Sorrentino (Italy)  In this class, Jennifer Lozano leads a U.S. team composed entirely of Olympic rookies.  Gold:Huang Hsiao-wen (Taiwan)Silver:Yeni Arias (Colombia)Bronze:Jutamas Jitpong (Thailand)Bronze:Munguntsetseg Enkhjargal (Mongolia)  No Taiwanese boxer has won Olympic gold.\\u00c2  Gold:Irma Testa (Italy)Silver:Svetlana Staneva (Bulgaria)Bronze:Esra Y\\u00c4\\u00b1ld\\u00c4\\u00b1z (Turkiye)Bronze:Karina Ibragimova (Kazakhstan)  At 2023 Worlds, Testa won the quarters, semis and finals each by 5\\u00e2\\u0080\\u00930 scores.\\u00c2  Gold:Beatriz Ferreira (Brazil)Silver:Estelle Mossely (France)Bronze:Oh Yeon Ji (South Korea)Bronze:Yang Wenlu (China)  Mossely\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s husband, Tony Yoka, was a boxing gold medalist in 2016.\\u00c2  Gold:Yang Liu (China)Silver:Janjaem Suwannapheng (Thailand)Bronze:Beatriz Soares (Brazil)Bronze:Busenaz S\\u00c3\\u00bcrmeneli (Turkiye)  S\\u00c3\\u00bcrmeneli is the reigning Olympic and two-time champ at this weight class.\\u00c2\\u00a0\\u00c2  Gold:Tammara Thibeault (Canada)Silver:Atheyna Bylon (Panama)Bronze:Rady Gramane (Mozambique)Bronze:Li Qian (China)  Thibault has a B.S. in linguistics with minors in Spanish and Mandarin.  Gold:Danis Civil (France)Silver:Victor Montalvo (U.S.)Bronze:Philip Kim (Canada)  Civil, aka Dany Dann, is a nurse born in French Guiana.  Gold:Dominika\\u00c2\\u00a0 Banevic (Lithuania)Silver:India Sardjoe (Netherlands)Bronze:Liu Qingyi (China)\\u00c2  The 35-year-old Queen from Queens, Sunny Choi is a strong U.S. contender.\\u00c2  Gold:Sebastian Brendel (Germany)Silver:Martin Fuksa (Czechia)Bronze:C\\u00c4\\u0083t\\u00c4\\u0083lin Chiril\\u00c4\\u0083 (Romania)  At 36, Brendel has amassed 30 world and Olympic medals.\\u00c2  Gold:Peter Kreschmer and Tim Hecker (Germany)Silver:Liu Hao and Ji Bowen (China)Bronze:Adrien Bart and Loic Leonard (France)  Kreschmer won gold at this event with another partner at the 2012 Olympics in London.  Gold:Fernando Pimenta (Portugal)Silver:Tom Green (Australia)Bronze:\\u00c3\\u0081d\\u00c3\\u00a1m Varga (Hungary)  Among other honors, Pimenta is a Grand Officer of the Order of Prince Henry.  Gold:Bence Na\\u00cc\\u0081das and S\\u00c3\\u00a1ndor T\\u00c3\\u00b3tka (Hungary)Silver:Jo\\u00c3\\u00a3o Ribeiro and Messias Baptista (Portugal)Bronze:Jean van der Westhuyzen and Tom Green (Australia)  At the 2023 Worlds, the top eight kayaks were separated by nine-tenths of a second.\\u00c2  Gold:GermanySilver:UkraineBronze:Hungary  Germany returns three of the four canoeists who won gold in this event in Tokyo.  Gold:Yarisleidis Cirilo Duboy (Cuba)Silver:Nevin Harrison (U.S.)Bronze:Lin Wenjun (China)  Harrison won her first world title in 2019 at age 17.\\u00c2  Gold:Xu Shixiao and Sun Mengya (China)Silver:Ant\\u00c3\\u00ada J\\u00c3\\u00a1come and Mar\\u00c3\\u00ada Corbera (Spain)Bronze:Katie Vincent and Sloan MacKenzie (Canada)  Xu and Sun struck gold when this event made its Olympic debut in Tokyo.\\u00c2  Gold:Lisa Carrington (New Zealand)Silver:Emma J\\u00c3\\u00b8rgensen (Denmark)Bronze:Tamara Csipes (Hungary)  At 35, Carrington has already won five golds over the last three Olympics.\\u00c2  Gold:Emma J\\u00c3\\u00b8rgensen and Frederikke Matthiesen (Denmark)Silver:Paulina Paszek and Jule Hake (Germany)Bronze:Martyna Klatt and Helena Wisniewska (Poland)  Paszek is a native of Poland, one of her pair\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s rivals.\\u00c2  Gold:New ZealandSilver:SpainBronze:Poland  New Zealand\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Alicia Hoskin underwent heart surgery in 2017.\\u00c2  Gold:Ben Sav\\u00c5\\u00a1ek (Slovenia)Silver:Luka\\u00cc\\u0081s\\u00cc\\u008c Rohan (Czechia)Bronze:Nicolas Gestin (France)  Sav\\u00c5\\u00a1ek has been in the top 10 of the overall World Cup standings since 2009.\\u00c2  Gold:Joe Clarke (Great Britain)Silver:Jiri Prskavec (Czechia)Bronze:Mathis Soudi (Morocco)  French-born Soudi would be the first Olympic canoe-kayak medalist from Morocco.\\u00c2  Gold:Joe Clarke (Great Britain)Silver:Martin Dougoud (Switzerland)Bronze:Boris Neveu (France)  Clarke angrily opposed his non-selection to the British team in Tokyo.\\u00c2  Gold:Mallory Franklin (Great Britain)Silver:Jessica Fox (Australia)Bronze:Kimberley Woods (Great Britain)  Third at Worlds in 2022, Monica Doria could become Andorra\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s first Olympic medalist.\\u00c2  Gold:Jessica Fox (Australia)Silver:Ricarda Funk (Germany)Bronze:Maialen Chourraut (Spain)  Fox\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s mother competed for France. Her father competed for Great Britain.\\u00c2  Gold:Camille Prigent (France)Silver:Kimberley Woods (Great Britain)Bronze:Eva Tercelj (Slovenia)  Prigent\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s father, Jean-Yves and brother, Yves, both won world slalom medals.\\u00c2  Gold:Joris Daudet (France)Silver:Sylvain Andr\\u00c3\\u00a9 (France)Bronze:Romain Mahieu (France)  How dominant is France? World silver in 2023, Arthur Pilard didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t qualify for the Olympics.\\u00c2  Gold:Logan Martin (Australia)Silver:Kieran Reilly (Great Britain)Bronze:Anthony Jeanjean (France)  Reilly gained fame when he landed a 720 as an 11-year-old.\\u00c2  Gold:Bethany Shriever (Great Britain)Silver:Alise Willoughby (U.S.)Bronze:Saya Sakakibara (Australia)  Willoughby crashed in a prelim in Tokyo, where Shriever won gold.\\u00c2  Gold:Hannah Roberts (U.S.)Silver:Charlotte Worthington (Great Britain)Bronze:Iveta Miculycov\\u00c3\\u00a1 (Czechia)  Miculycov\\u00c3\\u00a1 was 16 when she won the European Championship despite a hematoma in her leg.\\u00c2  Gold:Tom Pidcock (Great Britain)Silver:Sam Gaze (New Zealand)Bronze:David Valero (Spain)  Pidcock won gold in Tokyo two months after breaking his collarbone.\\u00c2  Gold:Pauline Ferrand-Prevot (France)Silver:Puck Pieterse (Netherlands)Bronze:Jolanda Neff (Switzerland)  In 2015, Ferrand-Prevost became the first cyclist to hold world titles in mountain bike, road and cyclo-cross events.  Gold:Mathieu van der Poel (Netherlands)Silver:Remco Evenepoel (Belgium)Bronze:Tadej Pogacar (Slovenia)  Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s mountain bike favorite Pidcock could pull off a tough double here.\\u00c2  Gold:Josh Tarling (Great Britain)Silver:Filippo Ganna (Italy)Bronze:Remco Evenepoel (Belgium)  Tarling and Ganna are also eyeing tough doubles with races on the track, too.\\u00c2  Gold:Lotte Kopecky (Belgium)Silver:Demi Vollering (Netherlands)Bronze:Marianne Vos (Netherlands)  Vos won Olympic golds in the road and track\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s points race. She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 37 now.\\u00c2  Gold:Ellen van Dijk (Netherlands)Silver:Chlo\\u00c3\\u00a9 Dygert (U.S.)Bronze:Demi Vollering (Netherlands)  Van Dijk started her sporting career as a competitive speed skater.\\u00c2  Gold:Harrie Lavreysen (Netherlands)Silver:Nicholas Paul (Trinidad and Tobago)Bronze:Mateusz Rudyk (Poland)  Not only Trinidad, but also Suriname (Jair Tjon En Fa), could win its first Olympic cycling medals here.  Gold:Kevin Quintero (Colombia)Silver:Harrie Lavreysen (Netherlands)Bronze:Matthew Glaetzer (Australia)\\u00c2  Glaetzer has overcome thyroid cancer.\\u00c2  Gold:Benjamin Thomas (France)Silver:I\\u00c3\\u00bari Leit\\u00c3\\u00a3o (Portugal)Bronze:Ethan Hayter (Great Britain)\\u00c2  The 28-year-old Thomas won a silver in omnium at the 2023 world championships.  Gold:Yoeri Havik and Jan-Willem van Schip (Netherlands)Silver:Ethan Hayter and Oliver Wood (Great Britain)Bronze:Benjamin Thomas and Thomas Boudat (France)  Havik recalls crying and ranting to coax his parents to purchase his first bike.  Gold:NetherlandsSilver:AustraliaBronze:Great Britain  The Dutch snapped Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s three-Games win streak in Tokyo by less than a tenth of a second.\\u00c2  Gold:DenmarkSilver:Great BritainBronze:Italy  The Italians snapped Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s three-Games win streak in Tokyo by less than two-tenths of a second.  Gold:Emma Finucane (Great Britain)Silver:Lea Friedrich (Germany)Bronze:Mathilde Gros (France)  Friedrich has won silver at the last three world championships.\\u00c2  Gold:Ellesse Andrews (New Zealand)Silver:Lea Friedrich (Germany)Bronze:Martha Bayona (Colombia)  Andrews was born 15 minutes shy of the year 2000.\\u00c2  Gold:Jennifer Valente (U.S.)Silver:Lotte Kopecky (Belgium)Bronze:Ally Wollaston (New Zealand)  Valente won this event handily at the Tokyo Games.\\u00c2  Gold:Neah Evans and Elinor Barker (Great Britain)Silver:Marion Borras and Clara Copponi (France)Bronze:Georgia Baker and Alex Manly (Australia)  Evans worked as a veterinary surgeon before becoming a full-time pro cyclist.\\u00c2  Gold:GermanySilver:ChinaBronze:Great Britain  Britain leads all nations in Olympic track cycling golds (33) and total medals (78).\\u00c2  Gold:Great BritainSilver:FranceBronze:New Zealand  British Olympic champ Katie Archibald suffered a broken leg and will miss the Games.\\u00c2  Gold:Wang Zongyuan (China)Silver:Osmar Olvera (Mexico)Bronze:Xie Siyi (China)  Olvera is the reigning world champ in the 1-meter event not contested at the Games.\\u00c2  Gold:Cassiel Rousseau (Australia)Silver:Yang Hao (China)Bronze:Cao Yuan (China)  Rousseau\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s grandfather, Michel Rousseau, won Olympic gold in cycling in 1956.\\u00c2  Gold:Wang Zongyuan and Long Daoyi (China)Silver:Jules Bouyer and Alexis Jandard (France)Bronze:Anthony Harding and Jack Laugher (Great Britain)\\u00c2  With 47 Olympic diving golds, China trails only the U.S. by two. Expect that to change in Paris.\\u00c2  Gold:Yang Hao and Lian Junjie (China)Silver:Matty Lee and Noah Williams (Great Britain)Bronze:Kirill Boliukh and Oleksiy Sereda (Ukraine)\\u00c2  In Tokyo, Lee won gold with Tom Daley by a single point to prevent a Chinese sweep of eight events.\\u00c2  Gold:Chen Yiwen (China)Silver:Maddison Keeney (Australia)Bronze:Chang Yani (China)  A Chinese diver has won this event at nine straight Olympics.  Gold:Quan Hongchan (China)Silver:Chen Yuxi (China)Bronze:Caeli McKay (Canada)  Quan was introduced to diving after a local coach saw her playing hopscotch.\\u00c2  Gold:Chen Yiwen and Chang Yani (China)Silver:Yasmin Harper and Scarlett Mew Jensen (Great Britain)Bronze:Sarah Bacon and Kassidy Cook (U.S.)  At 27, Bacon is a first-time Olympian after seven back fractures.  Gold:Chen Yuxi and Quan Hongchan (China)Silver:Andrea Spendolini-Sirieix and Lois Toulson (Great Britain)Bronze:Jessica Parratto and Delaney Schnell (U.S.)  Perrato\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s dad, Mike, coached Olympic swim great Jenny Thompson.\\u00c2\\u00a0\\u00c2  Gold:Charlotte Fry (Great Britain)Silver:Cathrine Laudrup-Dufour (Denmark)Bronze:Isabell Werth (Germany)\\u00c2  At 55, Werth has won medals at six Olympics.  Gold:Yasmin Ingham (Great Britain)Silver:Sandra Auffarth (Germany)Bronze:Tim Price (New Zealand)  Price\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s wife, Jonelle, won an eventing medal for the Kiwis in 2012.\\u00c2  Gold:Henrik von Eckermann (Sweden)Silver:Ben Maher (Great Britain)Bronze:Philipp Weishaupt (Germany)  Germany leads all countries with 28 Olympic equestrian golds and 56 medals.\\u00c2  Gold:DenmarkSilver:GermanyBronze:Great Britain\\u00c2  Denmark has won six Olympic equestrian medals, but never gold.\\u00c2  Gold:Great BritainSilver:FranceBronze:Australia  After a heavy fall 11 years ago, Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Laura Collett was placed in an induced coma for six days.\\u00c2  Gold:SwedenSilver:NetherlandsBronze:Great Britain  Equestrian is the one Olympic sport in which men and women compete together in every event.  Gold:Davide Di Veroli (Italy)Silver:Mate Koch (Hungary)Bronze:Romain Cannone (France)  Cannone learned fencing on the Lower East Side of New York when his family lived in the U.S.\\u00c2  Gold:Tommaso Marini (Italy)Silver:Kyosuke Matsuyama (Japan)Bronze:Nick Itkin (U.S.)  Itkin is the first U.S. man to win individual medals at consecutive world championships.\\u00c2  Gold:Eli Dershwitz (U.S.)Silver:\\u00c3\\u0081ron Szil\\u00c3\\u00a1gyi (Hungary)Bronze:Sandro Bazadze (Georgia)  Dershwitz\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s maternal grandparents were Holocaust survivors.\\u00c2  Gold:ItalySilver:FranceBronze:Venezuela  Rare South American medalist Venezuela scored one-point wins against Spain and Hungary for world bronze in 2023.\\u00c2  Gold:ItalySilver:FranceBronze:China  Italy has the most golds in men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s fencing, 39, one more than France, which has the most medals, 104, one more than Italy.\\u00c2  Gold:South KoreaSilver:HungaryBronze:U.S.  Once-powerful Hungary won this event at seven straight Olympics from 1928 to \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009960.\\u00c2  Gold:Marie-Florence Candassamy (France)Silver:Alberta Santuccio (Italy)Bronze:Vivian Kong (Hong Kong)  Hong Kong still competes separately from China at the Olympics.\\u00c2  Gold:Alice Volpi (Italy)Silver:Arianna Errigo (Italy)Bronze:Lee Kiefer (U.S.)  Defending champ Kiefer married Olympic foilist Gerek Meinhardt in 2019.\\u00c2  Gold:Misaki Emura (Japan)Silver:Despina Georgiadou (Greece)Bronze:Yoana Ilieva (Bulgaria)  No Japanese woman has won an Olympic fencing medal.\\u00c2  Gold:PolandSilver:ItalyBronze:South Korea  These were also the standing at the 2023 Worlds. They were reversed in \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009922.\\u00c2  Gold:ItalySilver:FranceBronze:Japan  The U.S. women will also contend for a medal here.\\u00c2  Gold:HungarySilver:FranceBronze:Spain  This is a huge jump for Hungary, which placed eighth in Tokyo.\\u00c2  Gold:BelgiumSilver:GermanyBronze:Australia  Belgian defender Alexander Hendrickx led all scorers at the Tokyo Games with 14 goals.\\u00c2  Gold:NetherlandsSilver:ArgentinaBronze:Germany\\u00c2  At the 2022 World Cup, Argentines won top scorer, best player and best goalkeeper, but still fell to the Dutch.  Gold:Scottie Scheffler (U.S.)Silver:Rory McIlroy (Ireland)Bronze:Xander Schauffele (U.S.)  Schauffele carded a second-round 63 en route to a one-stroke victory in Tokyo.\\u00c2  Gold:Nelly Korda (U.S.)Silver:Celine Boutier (France)Bronze:Yin Ruoning (China)  Korda carded a second-round 62 en route to a one-stroke victory in Tokyo.\\u00c2  Gold:JapanSilver:ChinaBronze:Bulgaria  The U.S. men could challenge for bronze.\\u00c2  Gold:Daiki Hashimoto (Japan)Silver:Ilya Kovtun (Ukraine)Bronze:Fred Richard (U.S.)  Richard has nearly a million followers on his social-media platforms.  Gold:Artem Dolgopyat (Israel)Silver:Carlos Yulo (Philippines)Bronze:Milad Karimi (Kazakhstan)  Reigning champ Dolgopyat was born in Ukraine.\\u00c2  Gold:Rhys Mcclenaghan (Ireland)Silver:Max Whitlock (Great Britain)Bronze:Ahmad Abu Al-Soud (Jordan)  The best on the U.S. team, Stephen Nedoroscik, does only this event.\\u00c2  Gold:Liu Yang (China)Silver:Eleftherios Petrounias (Greece)Bronze:Asher Hong (U.S.)  Parkour practitioner Petrounias has two screws holding a finger in place and twice underwent hernia surgery.  Gold:Jake Jarman (Great Britain)Silver:Nazar Chepurnyi (Ukraine)Bronze:Artur Davtyan (Armenia)  Armenia has won 18 Olympic medals, but only two golds.\\u00c2  Gold:Lukas Dauser (Germany)Silver:Zou Jingyuan (China)Bronze:Fred Richard (U.S.)  A coach noticed Zou and brought him into gymnastics at age 3.\\u00c2  Gold:Daiki Hashimoto (Japan)Silver:Tin Srbic (Croatia)Bronze:Milad Karimi (Kazakhstan)  Srbic was 6 when he broke two bones in his arm falling off the bar. It didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t stop him.\\u00c2  Gold:U.S.Silver:FranceBronze:Brazil  U.S. women have won a team medal at eight straight Olympics.  Gold:Simone Biles (U.S.)Silver:Rebeca Andrade (Brazil)Bronze:Qiu Qiyuan (China)  Biles has won an astounding 23 gold medals at world championships; four at the Olympics.\\u00c2  Gold:Simone Biles (U.S.)Silver:Rebeca Andrade (Brazil)Bronze:Jade Carey (U.S.)  Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s three-time European champ Jessica Gadirova is out with a torn ACL.\\u00c2  Gold:Kaylia Nemour (Algeria)Silver:Suni Lee (U.S.)Bronze:Qiu Qiyuan (China)  Algeria has never won an Olympic gymnastics medal.\\u00c2  Gold:Zhou Yaqin (China)Silver:Rebeca Andrade (Brazil)Bronze:Simone Biles (U.S.)  Andrade and her seven siblings were raised by a single mom who cleaned houses to support them.\\u00c2  Gold:Simone Biles (U.S.)Silver:Sabrina Voinea (Romania)Bronze:Rebeca Andrade (Brazil)  No other woman has completed Biles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s triple-twisting double back tuck tumbling pass in competition.  Gold:Darja Varfolomeev (Germany)Silver:Sofia Raffaeli (Italy)Bronze:Daria Atamanov (Israel)  Russian-born Varfolomeev won five golds at the 2023 Worlds in Spain.  Gold:BulgariaSilver:SpainBronze:Israel  The Russian group won medals at all seven Olympics that held the event.  Gold:Yan Langyu (China)Silver:Ivan Litvinovich (AIN)Bronze:Ryusei Nishioka (Japan)  Litvinovich was granted Individual Neutral Athletes (AIN) status despite signing a letter of support for Belarusian President Aleksandr Lukashenko.\\u00c2\\u00a0\\u00c2  Gold:Bryony Page (Great Britain)Silver:Zhu Xueying (China)Bronze:Hikaru Mori (Japan)  World champ Page wrote her university dissertation about sounds made by dinosaurs.\\u00c2  Gold:DenmarkSilver:FranceBronze:Spain  At 40, France\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Serbian-born Nikola Karabatic could become the sport\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s first four-time Olympic champ.  Gold:FranceSilver:NorwayBronze:Sweden  A Nordic nation has won an Olympic medal each year since 1988.  Gold:Francisco Garrig\\u00c3\\u00b3s (Spain)Silver:Giorgi Sardalashvili (Georgia)Bronze:Dilshodbek Baratov (Uzbekistan)Bronze:Enkhtaivan Ariunbold (Mongolia)  Mongolia has won 30 Olympic medals, but only two golds.  Gold:Hifumi Abe (Japan)Silver:Walide Khyar (France)Bronze:Denis Vieru (Moldova)Bronze:An Baul (South Korea)  Abe has won four world titles and also took gold at the Tokyo Games.  Gold:Nils Stump (Switzerland)Silver:Soichi Hashimoto (Japan)Bronze:Manuel Lombardo (Italy)Bronze:Hidayat Heydarov (Azerbaijan)  Stump became Switzerland\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s first world judo champ in 2023.  Gold:Tato Grigalashvili (Georgia)Silver:Matthias Casse (Belgium)Bronze:Wachid Borchashvili (Austria)Bronze:Takanori Nagase (Japan)  Casse became Belgium\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s first world judo champ in 2021.  Gold:Lasha Bekauri (Georgia)Silver:Davlat Bobonov (Uzbekistan)Bronze:Marcus Nyman (Sweden)Bronze:Ivan Silva Morales (Cuba)  Bekauri lost to teammate Luka Maisuradze in the 2023 world final. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s one per country per weight class at the Olympics.\\u00c2  Gold:Lukas Krpalek (Czechia)Silver:Zelym Kotsoiev (Azerbaijan)Bronze:Muzaffarbek Turoboyev (Uzbekistan)Bronze:Ilia Sulamanidze (Georgia)  Two-time champ Krpalek started judo when his uncle thought he was enrolling him in karate.\\u00c2  Gold:Teddy Riner (France)Silver:Temur Rakhimov (Tajikistan)Bronze:Rafael Silva (Brazil)Bronze:Alisher Yusupov (Uzbekistan)  Riner, 35, has won golds at the last three Olympics and is considered the GOAT by many.  Gold:Natsu